Of the 23 first year male students at State U. admitted for Jim Thorpe High School, 8 were offered baseball scholarships and 7 were offered football scholarships. The University admissions committee looked at the students composite ACT scores wondering if the University was lowering their standards for athletes. Assuming that this group of students is representative of all admitted students, what do you think?

Baseball <- c(25, 22, 19, 25, 24, 25, 24, 23)
NonAthletes <- c(21, 27, 29, 26, 30, 27, 26, 23)
Football <- c(22, 21, 24, 27, 19, 23, 17, NA)
DF2 <- stack(data.frame(Baseball, NonAthletes, Football))
colnames(DF2) <- list("ACT", "Sport")
head(DF2)
##   ACT    Sport
## 1  25 Baseball
## 2  22 Baseball
## 3  19 Baseball
## 4  25 Baseball
## 5  24 Baseball
## 6  25 Baseball
mod <- aov(ACT~Sport, data=DF2)
summary(mod)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## Sport        2   71.0   35.50   4.563 0.0233 *
## Residuals   20  155.6    7.78                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 1 observation deleted due to missingness
TukeyHSD(mod)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = ACT ~ Sport, data = DF2)
## 
## $Sport
##                           diff        lwr      upr     p adj
## Football-Baseball    -1.517857 -5.1701768 2.134463 0.5541765
## NonAthletes-Baseball  2.750000 -0.7784760 6.278476 0.1452038
## NonAthletes-Football  4.267857  0.6155375 7.920177 0.0204005
  1. Test an appropriate hypothesis and state your conclusion. Specify the null and alternative hypotheses with both mathematical symbols and with a verbal (English) description.

\(H_0:\mu_{Baseball} = \mu_{NonAthletes} = \mu_{Football}\) versus \(H_A:\mu_{i} \neq \mu_{j}\) for at least one \(i \neq j\) pair. Null Hypothesis- Baseball, Non Athletes and Football players have no association with their ACT score. Alternative Hypothesis- Baseball, Non Athletes and Football players have an association with their ACT score. Conclusion- The null hypothesis is rejected because the p value is less than 0.05. Therefore the data supports the alternative hypothsis that the average ACT score of a football or baseball player is lower than that of a non athlete.

  1. Are the two sports teams mean ACT scores different?

No, the mean scores for football players and baseball players is not significantly different.

Use the data frame Snore from the BSDA package to determine if snoring and heart-disease are related.

library(BSDA)
## Loading required package: e1071
## Loading required package: lattice
## 
## Attaching package: 'BSDA'
##

## 
##     Orange
head(Snore)

## 1   yes   24       35     21    30
## 2    no 1355      603    192   224
Snore[,2:5]
##    Non occasion nearly every
## 1   24       35     21    30
## 2 1355      603    192   224
chisq.test(Snore[, 2:5])
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  Snore[, 2:5]
## X-squared = 72.782, df = 3, p-value = 1.082e-15
  1. Write the null and alternative hypotheses.

Null Hypothesis: heart condition and snoring are independent. Alternative Hypothesis: heart condition and snoring are dependent.

  1. Test your null hypothesis and state your conclusion?
    Reject, the null hypothesis because the variables are dependent, which is supported by the p value (1.082e-15) that is determined by the chi square test. Therefore the data supports the alternative hypothesis.

  2. Do you need to run any post-hoc tests? If so, how many post-hoc tests do you need to examine? If indicated, perform the post-hoc tests and interpret your findings. Yes, run a chi square test (found above). Which determines that the variables are dependent.
